se hangs even on short connections. Use a sorted\n   linked list (not a timer wheel -- SLIRP creates ~10 timers, not thousands).\n   Drive from the event loop's poll timeout.\n\n4. **FD lookup for socket syscalls**: With shadow sockets, the guest calls\n   connect/getsockopt/etc with the host socketpair FD number. The primary\n   lookup `kbox_fd_table_get_lkl(fd)` will miss (it's not a virtual FD).\n   All socket-related dispatch handlers must use `kbox_fd_table_find_by_host_fd`\n   as a fallback -- same pattern as `forward_close` already does (line 489).\n   Without this, connect() falls through to CONTINUE and connects the\n   AF_UNIX socketpair instead of the LKL socket.\n\n5. **Dispatch routing for data syscalls**: sendto/recvfrom/sendmsg/recvmsg\n   are not in the BPF allow list. They arrive at the supervisor and currently\n   get ENOSYS. With shadow sockets, these must be explicitly dispatched as\n   CONTINUE so the host kernel handles them on the socketpair. The dispatch\n   must check whether the FD is a shadow socket (has host_fd set) and return\n   CONTINUE, or forward to LKL for non-shadow socket FDs.\n\n   read/write already do the right thing: `kbox_fd_table_get_lkl(host_fd)`\n   returns -1, so they fall through to CONTINUE on the host socketpair.\n\n6. **connect() semantics**: connect() must remain intercepted. The supervisor\n   extracts the target sockaddr from tracee memory, calls lkl_sys_connect on\n   the LKL socket (looked up via find_by_host_fd), and returns the result.\n\n   For non-blocking connect: lkl_sys_connect returns EINPROGRESS. The event\n   loop polls the LKL socket for writability. When ready, the supervisor\n   reads SO_ERROR from the LKL socket. To signal the guest, write a\n   zero-byte wakeup to the supervisor-end socketpair (makes the guest-end\n   readable/writable for poll). getsockopt(SO_ERROR) must be intercepted\n   and forwarded to LKL, not the host socketpair.\n\n7. **Phasing**:\n   - Phase 1 (outbound only): DNS (UDP) + 